        {"pearl": "The testicles are typically viable even when the scrotal skin is completely necrotic, because their blood supply comes from the internal spermatic arteries (aortic origin) rather than the perineal vessels. After debridement, the testicles can be placed in subcutaneous thigh pouches or covered with moist saline dressings. They should NOT be debrided.", "LOE": "4", "pearlType": "operative"},
        {"pearl": "A colostomy (diverting sigmoid colostomy) should be considered in patients with extensive perineal involvement, especially if the anus or anal canal is involved or if fecal contamination of the wound is inevitable. Fecal diversion reduces wound contamination and accelerates healing. A temporary colostomy can be reversed once healing is complete.", "LOE": "4", "pearlType": "operative"}
